Wine Quality Prediction Project

Project Overview

The purpose of this project is to practice data mining and statistical learning using the public wine dataset. More specifically, in this project, I create a predictive model on the quality of red wine based on chemical properties of wine.

library(magrittr)

white_wine_dataset <- read.csv(here::here("data-raw", "winequality-white.csv"), 
                               header = TRUE, 
                               sep = ";")

Data Preparation

white_col_list <-
  colnames(white_wine_dataset[1:11]) %<>%
  gsub("[[:punct:]]", "_", .) %>%
  gsub("[[:space:]]", "_", .)

renamed_white_wine <-
  paste0(tolower(white_col_list))
  
white_wine_dataset %>%
  dplyr::rename_at(1:11, ~renamed_white_wine) %>%
  saveRDS(here::here("data", "white_wine_dataset.rds"))

Objectives

We want to make a predictive model on the quality of white wine based on chemical properties of wine.

The following analytical approaches are taken:

  • Multiple regression: the Quality response is assumed to be a continuous variable and is predicted by the independent predictors, all of which are continuous.
  • Regression Tree
  • Classification of wines based on the chemical properties: Unsupervised analysis
  • Classification of wines based on the chemical properties: K-nearest neighbors classification

Exploratory Data Analysis and Data Preprocessing

All white wine data set variables are summarized and univariate analysis with plots are shown.

Histograms

We start with histograms to show the distribution of the variable values.

Boxplots

We also utilize boxplots to get a different view of the spread.

Observations

Main observation is that all variables contain outliers.

  • Based on the histogram for Quality, the most concentrated values are in [5, 6, 7]. Only a small proportion in in categories [3, 4, 8], and none in [1, 2, 9].
  • Fixed Acidity, Volatile Acidity, Citric Acid all have outliers. If those outliers are eliminated, the distribution of the variables may take a more symmetric form.
  • Residual Sugar has a positively skewed distribution. This distribution will remain true regardless of whether the outliers are removed.
  • Most of the outliers are on the larger side.
  • Alcohol shows an irregularly shaped distribution, but these outliers are not as pronounced as the others.

Data Preparation

Possibly the most important step in data preparation is to identify outliers. Since we have a multivariate data, we consider only those points which do not have any predictore variable value to be outside of limits constructed by boxplots. Therefore, we apply the following rule:

  • A predictor value is considered to be an outlier only if it is greater than Q3 + 1.5IQR, where Q3 is the third quartile and we multiple the Inner Quartile Range by 1.5.

This is because the extreme outliers are all on the higher end of the values and the distributions are all positively skewed.

We then randomly divide our data into Training Data and Test Data of equal sizes (50% each).

limit_out <- rep(0, 11)

for (i in 1:11) {
  tile1 <- stats::quantile(white_wine[,i], 0.75)
  tile2 <- stats::IQR(white_wine[,i], 0.75)
  limit_out[i] <- tile1 + 1.5*tile2
}

WhiteWineIndex <- matrix(0, 4898, 11)
for (i in 1:4898)
  for (j in 1:11) {
    if (white_wine[i, j] > limit_out[j])
      WhiteWineIndex[i, j] <- 1
  }
WWInd <- apply(WhiteWineIndex, 1, sum)
WhiteWineTemp <- cbind(WWInd, white_wine)
Indexes <- rep(0, 208)
j <- 1
for (i in 1:4898) {
  if (WWInd[i] > 0) {
    Indexes[j] <- i
    j <- j + 1
  }
  else
    j <- j
}

WhiteWineLib <- white_wine[-Indexes, ]   # Inside of Q3+1.5IQR
indexes = sample(1:nrow(WhiteWineLib), size = 0.5 * nrow(WhiteWineLib))
white_wine_train <- WhiteWineLib[indexes, ]
white_wine_test <- WhiteWineLib[-indexes, ]

white_wine_train %>%
  saveRDS(here::here("data", "white_wine_train.rds"))
white_wine_test %>%
  saveRDS(here::here("data", "white_wine_test.rds"))

Looking for our model

Linear Regression is fitted to the training data.

We also look at the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) to detect multicollinearity in regression analysis. Multicollinearity is when theres correlation between predictors in a model; its presence can adveresly affect the regression results. The VIF estimates how much the variance of a regression coefficient is inflated due to multicollinearity in the model.

We also investigate the Box-Cox plot

MASS::boxcox(stats::lm(quality ~ alcohol), 
             data = white_wine_train, lambda = seq(-0.2, 1.0, len = 20), 
             plotit = T)

Outliers and leverage points are identified through the following:

  • Studentized deleted residuals - a point is an outlier if residual is outside of [-3, 3] limits
  • DFITS - a point is an outlier if residual is outside of [-1, 1] limits
  • Cooks Distance
studentized_deleted_residuals <- MASS::studres(fitness_3)
MASS::truehist(studentized_deleted_residuals, h = 0.25, col = "slategray3")
graphics::mtext("Histogram of Studentized Deleted Residuals", side = 1, line = 2, cex = 0.8)

# Larger bin width
graphics::par(mfrow=c(1,2), oma = c(3,2,3,2) + 0.1, mar = c(1,1,1,1) + 0.1)
MASS::truehist(studentized_deleted_residuals, h = 0.55, col = "slategray3")
graphics::mtext("Studentized deleted residuals", side = 1, line = 2, cex = 0.8)

deletion_fits <- stats::dffits(fitness_3)
MASS::truehist(deletion_fits, h = 0.25, col = "slategray3")

# Smaller bin width

No point is an outlier with the DFITS value.

Final Model

Only 26 points are identified as outliers according to the above criteria. A final model is fit after eliminating these points.

final_model <- stats::lm(quality ~ stats::poly(alcohol, 2) + stats::poly(volatile_acidity, 2) + residual_sugar 
                         + stats::poly(free_sulfur_dioxide, 2) + chlorides + sulphates + stats::poly(ph, 2),
                         white_wine_train)
